04543nam a22007095i 9780271072210DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211993pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710722107 a10.1515/97802710722102doi  a(DE-B1597)583874  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR9492.2.A4 1993 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a8231 aAfzal-Khan, Fawzia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCultural Imperialism and the Indo-English Novel :bGenre and Ideology in R. K. Narayan, Anita Desai, Kamala Markandaya, and Salman Rushdie /cFawzia Afzal-Khan. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Realm of Mythic Realism -- t2 The Morality of Realism Versus the Aestheticism of Myth -- t3 Myth Versus Realism or East Versus West -- t4 The Debunking of Myth -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCultural Imperialism and the Indo-English Novel focuses on the novels of R. K. Narayan, Anita Desai, Kamala Markandaya, and Salman Rushdie and explores the tension in these novels between ideology and the generic fictive strategies that shape ideology or are shaped by it. Fawzia Afzal-Khan raises the important question of how much the usage of certain ideological strategies actually helps the ex-colonized writer deal effectively with postcolonial and postindependence trauma and whether or not the choice of a particular genre or mode employed by a writer presupposes the extent to which that writer will be successful in challenging the ideological strategies of ";containment"; perpetuated by most Western ";orientalist"; texts and writers. She argues that the formal or generic choices of the four writers studied here reveal that they are using genre as an ideological ";strategy of liberation"; to help free their peoples and cultures from the hegemonic strategies of ";containment"; imposed upon them. She concludes that the works studied here constitute an ideological rebuttal of Western writers' denigrating ";containment"; of non-Western cultures. She also notes that self-criticism, as implied in Rushdie's works, is not be confused with self-hatred, a theme found in Naipaul's work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aImperialism in literature. 0aIndic fiction (English)zIndiaxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aDesai, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarkandaya, Kamala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarayan, R. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRushdie, Salman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271072210zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271072210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271072210.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK